            <title><![CDATA[Egypt’s Reme-D secures GIF backing to cut diagnostic costs by 40%]]></title>
                        <description><![CDATA[<ul>
	<li>Egypt-based biotech startup Reme-D has raised $500,000 from the Global Innovation Fund (GIF) to scale its molecular diagnostics solutions.</li>
	<li>Founded in 2022 by Salma Tammam, the company develops room-temperature PCR testing kits using nanotechnology and lyophilisation techniques.</li>
	<li>The technology eliminates cold-chain requirements, reducing diagnostic costs by up to 40% and improving reliability in low-resource settings.</li>
	<li>Reme-D currently operates across Egypt, Iraq, Sudan, and Kenya, serving 92 healthcare facilities and testing around 50,000 patients monthly.</li>
	<li>The funding will support expansion into Nigeria and Libya, production scaling, and R&amp;D in genetic diseases, oncology, and maternal health.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Press release:</strong></p>

<p>Egyptian biotech startup Reme-D has secured a $500,000 investment from the Global Innovation Fund (GIF) to expand its operations and scale accessible molecular diagnostics across Africa and the Middle East.</p>

<p>Founded in 2022, Reme-D develops PCR testing kits that remain stable at room temperature, eliminating the need for cold-chain logistics. By leveraging nanotechnology and lyophilisation techniques, the company enables cost-effective and reliable diagnostics in infrastructure-constrained environments.</p>

<p>The technology reduces operational costs by up to 40% while minimising reagent waste and improving testing reliability, particularly in regions with limited access to consistent electricity.</p>

<p>Reme-D has already established a growing footprint across Egypt, Iraq, Sudan, and Kenya, supporting 92 healthcare facilities and testing approximately 50,000 patients monthly. Its solutions have also reduced testing time by up to 70% in certain applications.</p>

<p>The new funding will support the company&rsquo;s next phase of growth, including commercial expansion into Nigeria and Libya, scaling manufacturing capabilities, and advancing research into genetic diseases, oncology, and maternal health diagnostics.</p>

<p>Reme-D&rsquo;s approach reflects a broader shift toward locally developed healthcare technologies designed to address real-world constraints, improving access to diagnostics across underserved populations.</p>]]></description>
